#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.h1:17-1
msgctxt "HTM_po_nelkul\\introduction_to_frames.htm+html.body.h1:17-1"
msgid "Introduction to Frames"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:18-1
msgid ""
"Frames are a quick, easy way to make your applications more accessible. A "
"frame is a rectangular area of a window or the screen you define so JAWS "
"knows to monitor it for any activity that might take place."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.h2:19-1
msgid "What Frames Do"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:20-1
msgid "Frames can do many things. Some of the more common uses are:"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:22-1
msgid "Speak or Braille information at the press of a keystroke."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:23-1
msgid ""
"Speak or Braille information when you <b>TAB</b> to a control within the "
"borders of the frame."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:24-1
msgid ""
"Speak or Braille information when text is newly displayed within the borders "
"of the frame."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:25-1
msgid "Prevent JAWS from automatically speaking information."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:27-1
msgid ""
"Quickly list all of your currently active frames by pressing <b>INSERT+F9</"
"b>. Select a frame in the list and press <b>ENTER</b> and the JAWS cursor is "
"moved to that frame."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:28-1
msgid ""
"Press <b>CTRL+INSERT+A</b> to quickly display the names and textual content "
"of all currently active frames within the Virtual Viewer. Easily select text "
"and copy it to the clipboard. Use standard reading commands to read the "
"information. Each frame's name is a link, and selecting one of these links "
"moves the JAWS cursor to that frame. This feature makes it very easy to "
"interact with text without moving focus away from the control or window "
"where you were working, and will save many people a lot of time in terminal "
"emulation programs, call centers, and many other situations."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.h2:29-1
msgid "Working with Frames"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:30-1
msgid ""
"Frames are now much easier to work with and modify. We provide a totally new "
"interface that is easier to use for everyone. In Frame Viewer, frames are "
"visible on the screen, and standard commands let you easily move between "
"them, move and resize them, and access their properties. Refer to <a "
"href=\"frame_viewer.htm\">Frame Viewer</a>."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:31-1
msgid ""
"Frames also provide the support to make it possible to quickly and easily "
"create prompts for controls when the prompt does not speak or does not "
"provide useful information. Refer to <a "
"href=\"Add_and_Change_Prompts.htm\">Add and Change Prompts</a>."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.h2:32-1
msgid "Designing Effective Frames"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:33-1
msgid "With frames, there are three main things to consider:"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:34-1
msgid ""
"<b style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Position</b>: Your frame needs to be "
"properly positioned. The frame's size and location determine what areas of "
"the screen or window are monitored. Frames should be positioned based on "
"what information you want them to speak, what you want them to do, or what "
"activity occurring in your application you wish to have cause the frame to "
"do something. Frames are positioned when they are first created, and easy to "
"use methods are provided for you to move or resize a frame within Frame "
"Viewer."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:35-1
msgid ""
"<b style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Validation Rules</b>: Frames set rules to "
"compare information in your application with information that is specified "
"when each frame is created. This ensures frames are only available where you "
"need to use them. Frames should be limited so they only work where you need "
"them. If you design a series of three or four frames to make a specific "
"dialog box in Microsoft Word more accessible, the frames should only be "
"active in that dialog box. If they are active in other Word dialog boxes, "
"you will receive unpredictable, and possibly very confusing results."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cintroduction_to_frames.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:36-1
msgid ""
"<b style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Events and Actions</b>: Events are the "
"activities that cause your frames to perform some action. Set your frames to "
"do something when a key is pressed, when text is newly displayed within the "
"borders of the frame, when you move to a control within the borders of a "
"frame, or when one of these events occur within another frame. Assign the "
"actions you wish to occur to each event, and a frame can do many things, "
"naturally responding as you work in your application."
msgstr ""

